ATLANTA, Dec. 1 (AP).—Bishop Costen J. Harrell of the Methodist Church died here Monday at the age of 86.

Bishop Harrell, who was elected in 1948, had been known internationally for his work in church organizations and for his studies of the Bible and worship.

After, serving as bishop of the Charlotte, N. C., area of the Methodist Church from 1948 to 1956, Bishop Harrell taught courses in worship, church policy and discipline at Emory's Candler School of Theology here until two years ago.

Before being elected bishop, he served pastorates at Raleigh, Durham and Wilson, N. C., Norfolk and Richmond, Va., and Nashville, Tenn. He was also pastor of the First Methodist Church here from 1920–1925.